If Rails receives a SAML response signed with NEW certificate, but Rails still has only OLD certificate configured…

Will Rails even attempt to verify using the certificate included in the response? Or will it reject immediately?

Think carefully about trust model.

###

rails will trust old certificate for verify signature and in that verification will fail and authentication doesn't happen


✅ Correct. That is exactly what will happen.

Let’s refine it slightly so you understand the trust model perfectly.

🔐 Scenario

Active Directory Federation Services rotates to NEW certificate

Rails still has only OLD certificate configured

ADFS signs SAML response with NEW private key

🔎 What Rails Does

1️⃣ Extracts <SignatureValue>
2️⃣ Uses configured OLD certificate
3️⃣ Attempts verification
4️⃣ Verification fails

Result:

❌ Signature validation error
❌ Authentication rejected
❌ User login fails

🧠 Important Security Detail

Rails will NOT:

Trust the certificate included in the SAML response

Dynamically switch to that certificate

Attempt to auto-learn a new cert

Because that would break the trust boundary.

The Service Provider must only trust pre-configured certificates.

🔐 Why This Is Secure

Imagine if Rails did this instead:

Extract cert from response

Use that cert to verify

An attacker could:

Generate own key pair

Sign fake SAML assertion

Attach their own certificate

Gain access

That’s why Rails only uses pre-trusted certificates.

🎯 Clean Interview Answer

If interviewer asks:

What happens if IdP rotates certificate but SP still trusts old one?

You say:

The Service Provider will attempt to verify the SAML signature using the configured trusted certificate. Since the Identity Provider is now signing with a different private key, signature verification will fail and authentication will be rejected until the new certificate is configured.

🔥 That’s architect-level clarity.

